{"query":"How does the scale of habitat features, such as field size and margin width, affect butterfly and moth communities on farmland?","summary":"Four replicated, site comparison studies found that landscapes with smaller fields had a higher abundance of butterflies and burnet moths than areas with larger fields (3974). Two of four replicated, site comparison studies found that areas with smaller fields had a higher species richness of butterflies and burnet moths, while two studies found similar species richness (3974). One before-and-after study found that reducing field size, along with other habitat improvements, increased the species richness of butterflies and burnet moths (3974).

Regarding margin width, two site comparison studies found that the species richness of butterflies was higher in longer or wider uncultivated margins than in shorter, narrower or conventional width margins (3981). Similarly, five replicated, site comparison studies found that wider grass margins (up to 6 m wide) had a greater species richness or diversity of butterflies and moths than narrower or conventional width margins (3982). However, one replicated, controlled study found that 2-m grass margins had a greater species richness of butterflies than cropped field edges, but 6-m grass margins did not (3982). For abundance, one study found that wide uncultivated margins had a higher abundance of butterflies than conventional margins (3981). Three of seven replicated, site comparison studies found that wider grass margins (up to 6 m wide) had a higher abundance of habitat-sensitive butterflies and moths than narrower or conventional width margins (3982).

More generally, nine of eleven studies found that the species richness of butterflies and moths was higher on farms with a greater proportion of semi-natural habitat (3910). Six replicated studies also found that the abundance of butterflies and moths was higher on farms with a greater proportion of semi-natural habitat (3910). Additionally, three of four site comparison studies found that established hedgerows had a higher species richness of butterflies and macro-moths than in-field beetle banks, crops or pasture (3976), and five of six studies found that the abundance of butterflies and moths was higher along hedgerows (3976).","action_ids":["3974","3981","3982","3910","3976"]}
